  "text": "The Rust compiler's type inference architecture is centered around three key components:\n\n1. **InferCtxt** (compiler/rustc_infer/src/infer/mod.rs): This is the main inference context struct that coordinates all type inference operations. It contains type variable storage, region constraints, unification tables, and tracks pending obligations. The InferCtxt is generic over lifetimes ('tcx) and serves as the central hub for type checking.\n\n2. **FnCtxt** (compiler/rustc_hir_typeck/src/fn_ctxt/mod.rs): This is the function-level type checker that wraps the InferCtxt with function-specific state. It manages the body_id, parameter environment (param_env), return type coercion tracking (ret_coercion), and function divergence tracking. FnCtxt is responsible for type checking function bodies, closures, and const expressions.\n\n3. **TypeVariableOrigin** (compiler/rustc_infer/src/infer/type_variable.rs): This struct (defined at line 94) tracks the origin of type variables created during inference. It contains a span and an optional param_def_id to track which type parameter a variable was instantiated for, primarily used for diagnostics.\n\nThese three components work together: InferCtxt provides the low-level inference machinery, TypeVariableOrigin tracks metadata about inference variables, and FnCtxt wraps everything for function-level type checking with additional context and state management."
}

